I'm thinking through the ClassLoader and how `getSystemClassLoader().loadClass(\\\"Installer\\\")` could lead to loading a fake Installer from test classes. It's tricky since both named and unnamed modules use the same loader. I need to consider whether `Module.canRead(unnamed)` returns false, which might complicate things. I'll need to modify the current test to locate the original jar on the classpath and define modules accordingly. It’s a bit convoluted, but it seems workable with some adjustments to avoid conflicts.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering module conflicts**\\n\\nI'm wondering if a classloader can define the named module `modelmapper` when its packages are already part of the classpath. It seems the class loader won't know until the definition happens. There’s a possibility it might be allowed since named module loading uses a module path. However, I’m concerned about potential conflicts with the test-generated Installer class, especially if the module lacks certain packages. I should keep in mind that the jar copy includes all the original entries.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_hxTkVtN9sgJwwhRUmf2tSGZR|fc_01e59afe7f0611f70169fc22ce7818819fb7eba76a1460caec", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "jar tf /home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.modelmapper/modelmapper/3.2.0/7664b15466a898625b394af6000439c5799a5d2b/modelmapper-3.2.0.jar | grep '^org/modelmapper/internal/bytebuddy/agent/[^/]*\\.class$' | head"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2435, "output": 1139, "cacheRead": 63488, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 67062, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778131643519, "responseId": "resp_01e59afe7f0611f70169fc22bcf1b4819f9199eed55b6cee0d"}}
